Build a cell-cycle classifer using FACS sorted data

Joyce Hsiao

2016-02-03

  • Background and objectives
  • Set up

  • Multinomial lasso

  • Session information

Background and objectives

Build a classifer that use gene expression patterns to predict cell-cycle stages. We use the FACS sorted data (Leng2015) in which cells are sorted into G1, S, and G2 and loaded on to independent C1 plates. Modulo batch effect, theres information to be exploited here about cell-cycle classification.

Set up

library("matrixStats")
library("glmnet")
library("knitr")
library("mygene")

cross-validation on the glmnet fit

cvfit <- cv.glmnet(x = t(cycle_data), 
                   y = cycle_vector, 
                   family="multinomial", 
                   type.multinomial = "ungrouped", parallel = TRUE)
## Warning: executing %dopar% sequentially: no parallel backend registered
plot(cvfit)

df_coef <- data.frame(v1 = matrix(coef(cvfit, s = "lambda.min")[[1]]),
                      v2 = matrix(coef(cvfit, s = "lambda.min")[[2]]),
                      v3 = matrix(coef(cvfit, s = "lambda.min")[[3]]) )
length(which(rowSums(df_coef != 0) > 0))
## [1] 93

Extract significant coefficients.

df_coef_selected <- df_coef[which(rowSums(df_coef != 0) > 0), ]
df_coef_relative_S <- data.frame(
    G1_to_S = df_coef_selected[ ,1] - df_coef_selected[ ,2], 
    G2_to_S = df_coef_selected[ ,3] - df_coef_selected[ ,2])
#round(df_coef_relative_S, 4)

Compute phase-specific mean gene expression for the selected genes.

cell_phases_cycle_data <- cell_phases[cell_phases != "H1"]
genes_selected <- gene_names[which(rowSums(df_coef != 0) > 0)]
data_selected <- log2(as.matrix(cycle_data[ as.character(gene_names) %in% genes_selected, ])+1)

cycle_means <-
  do.call(rbind, lapply(1:length(genes_selected), function(per_gene) {
      data.frame(G1 = mean(data_selected[per_gene, cell_phases_cycle_data == "G1"]),
                 S = mean(data_selected[per_gene, cell_phases_cycle_data == "S"]),
                 G2 = mean(data_selected[per_gene, cell_phases_cycle_data == "G2"]) )  
}))
fit_predict <- predict(cvfit, 
        newx = t(cycle_data[, sample(x = ncol(cycle_data), size = 50, replace = FALSE) ]) ,
        type="response", s=0.01)
round(fit_predict[1:20, ,],3)

ankyrin 3, node of Ranvier (ankyrin G) ANK3 288 Ankyrins are a family of proteins that are believed to link the integral membrane proteins to the underlying spectrin-actin cytoskeleton and play key roles in activities such as cell motility, activation, proliferation, contact, and the maintenance of specialized membrane domains. Multiple isoforms of ankyrin with different affinities for various target proteins are expressed in a tissue-specific, developmentally regulated manner. Most ankyrins are typically composed of three structural domains: an amino-terminal domain containing multiple ankyrin repeats; a central region with a highly conserved spectrin binding domain; and a carboxy-terminal regulatory domain which is the least conserved and subject to variation. Ankyrin 3 is an immunologically distinct gene product from ankyrins 1 and 2, and was originally found at the axonal initial segment and nodes of Ranvier of neurons in the central and peripheral nervous systems. Multiple transcript variants encoding different isoforms have been found for this gene. NA
